 - Hello, and welcome to our lecture about JavaScript.

2
00:00:03,960 --> 00:00:06,460
 JavaScript is another programming language,

3
00:00:06,460 --> 00:00:08,540
 and it's, if the Python is the only language you know,

4
00:00:08,540 --> 00:00:11,820
 it's quite a bit different than Python.

5
00:00:11,820 --> 00:00:15,140
 So JavaScript was originally designed

6
00:00:15,140 --> 00:00:18,380
 as an addition to HTML and CSS,

7
00:00:18,380 --> 00:00:21,340
 and it really started as a programming language

8
00:00:21,340 --> 00:00:24,600
 inside of the browser that runs right in the browser.

9
00:00:24,600 --> 00:00:28,420
 Even though it's named like JavaScript, like Java,

10
00:00:28,420 --> 00:00:32,280
 it's really more like Python in how it works,

11
00:00:32,280 --> 00:00:35,700
 and it, except that it has a C-like syntax.

12
00:00:35,700 --> 00:00:37,940
 And it's really an amazing language,

13
00:00:37,940 --> 00:00:40,060
 and a lot of people, for a lot of people,

14
00:00:40,060 --> 00:00:42,700
 it's their number one language, their favorite language,

15
00:00:42,700 --> 00:00:44,740
 and so it's worth learning JavaScript,

16
00:00:44,740 --> 00:00:46,740
 even if you love Python.

17
00:00:46,740 --> 00:00:51,860
 So JavaScript is an interesting language

18
00:00:51,860 --> 00:00:55,620
 in that it was built very quickly in 10 days in 1995

19
00:00:55,620 --> 00:00:57,460
 by a fellow named Brennan Icke.

20
00:00:57,460 --> 00:00:59,780
 Brennan was a PhD in physics,

21
00:00:59,780 --> 00:01:01,980
 and he knew a lot about programming languages

22
00:01:01,980 --> 00:01:05,940
 and formal languages and how to build compilers really fast.

23
00:01:05,940 --> 00:01:10,940
 And so the idea was to make a sort of a subversion of Java,

24
00:01:10,940 --> 00:01:12,540
 like a lightweight version of Java,

25
00:01:12,540 --> 00:01:14,340
 and put it in the browser.

26
00:01:14,340 --> 00:01:17,380
 Today, it's gone through a standardization process,

27
00:01:17,380 --> 00:01:19,580
 and it's called ECMA script.

28
00:01:19,580 --> 00:01:21,220
 And so if we were to take a look

29
00:01:21,220 --> 00:01:23,340
 at the history of programming languages,

30
00:01:25,260 --> 00:01:28,340
 you know, probably, oops, you know by now,

31
00:01:28,340 --> 00:01:30,020
 you know Python, right?

32
00:01:30,020 --> 00:01:33,900
 And Python is a great language,

33
00:01:33,900 --> 00:01:36,100
 and JavaScript is the other language we're gonna learn here.

34
00:01:36,100 --> 00:01:38,820
 And this just sort of puts them in some context

35
00:01:38,820 --> 00:01:42,340
 so that you understand a bit of the influences.

36
00:01:42,340 --> 00:01:46,220
 So in the very beginnings, in the '50s, 1950s,

37
00:01:46,220 --> 00:01:47,980
 we programmed in assembly language,

38
00:01:47,980 --> 00:01:49,700
 and then most computers,

39
00:01:49,700 --> 00:01:52,340
 all they could do is numeric calculations very well,

40
00:01:52,340 --> 00:01:55,260
 and so languages like Fortran came along.

41
00:01:55,260 --> 00:01:58,500
 Probably there's lots of languages,

42
00:01:58,500 --> 00:02:00,620
 and so if you go back to the '50s and the '60s,

43
00:02:00,620 --> 00:02:03,140
 people were inventing languages all the time.

44
00:02:03,140 --> 00:02:08,380
 But a language that really, for me, changed everything

45
00:02:08,380 --> 00:02:12,700
 was the C language, invented in 1972,

46
00:02:12,700 --> 00:02:16,140
 and I still wanna do a really cool class on C.

47
00:02:16,140 --> 00:02:18,220
 C's not a good language to write everything in.

48
00:02:18,220 --> 00:02:20,860
 It's very much like a assembly language.

49
00:02:20,860 --> 00:02:23,380
 It mirrors how computers really work,

50
00:02:23,380 --> 00:02:26,180
 which is kind of different than how we program computers

51
00:02:26,180 --> 00:02:27,740
 in a lot of ways.

52
00:02:27,740 --> 00:02:30,620
 But the other thing that C was doing was

53
00:02:30,620 --> 00:02:33,860
 it was acknowledging that computers

54
00:02:33,860 --> 00:02:37,220
 were less and less about numerical computations,

55
00:02:37,220 --> 00:02:41,740
 and more about strings, and you know words,

56
00:02:41,740 --> 00:02:44,380
 and messages, and things like that.

57
00:02:44,380 --> 00:02:49,380
 So if you, you know, it's probably 95% of the calculations

58
00:02:50,020 --> 00:02:52,740
 in computers have to do with moving data around,

59
00:02:52,740 --> 00:02:56,260
 not numbers around, and C was great at that.

60
00:02:56,260 --> 00:02:59,940
 So all the languages I used up till I started using C,

61
00:02:59,940 --> 00:03:02,540
 they were kind of a numeric system

62
00:03:02,540 --> 00:03:04,700
 that was sort of fighting to do characters well,

63
00:03:04,700 --> 00:03:07,180
 and the C was a very well done character system.

64
00:03:07,180 --> 00:03:09,900
 And so it became the language, C is the language

65
00:03:09,900 --> 00:03:11,980
 that's kind of the mother language of all this.

66
00:03:11,980 --> 00:03:16,980
 It's the Linux is written in C, Python is written in C,

67
00:03:17,580 --> 00:03:22,580
 PHP is written in C, JavaScript is probably written in C.

68
00:03:22,580 --> 00:03:26,620
 And so it's like the lowest level language

69
00:03:26,620 --> 00:03:28,020
 that we go to these days.

70
00:03:28,020 --> 00:03:30,260
 And when you're writing a language

71
00:03:30,260 --> 00:03:31,460
 and you want it to be fast,

72
00:03:31,460 --> 00:03:35,060
 the implementation of that language is often written in C.

73
00:03:35,060 --> 00:03:38,180
 C++ came from C as an object-oriented variation,

74
00:03:38,180 --> 00:03:40,100
 and we talked a lot about object-oriented Python.

75
00:03:40,100 --> 00:03:42,620
 We're gonna talk about object-oriented JavaScript coming up.

76
00:03:42,620 --> 00:03:47,620
 And so C++ influenced a whole lot of systems

77
00:03:47,620 --> 00:03:53,940
 that had to do in a sense C++ influenced Python as well.

78
00:03:53,940 --> 00:03:58,020
 And so C++ has added an object-oriented layer.

79
00:03:58,020 --> 00:04:00,420
 It's actually probably the least object-oriented

80
00:04:00,420 --> 00:04:03,500
 of any of these other languages on here,

81
00:04:03,500 --> 00:04:05,940
 but it had object-oriented concepts.

82
00:04:05,940 --> 00:04:09,740
 C# was Microsoft's version of that.

83
00:04:09,740 --> 00:04:14,740
 Java was open source, the thing that became

84
00:04:14,740 --> 00:04:18,100
 the sort of progenitor of JavaScript.

85
00:04:18,100 --> 00:04:20,860
 But again, they're not as related as you might think.

86
00:04:20,860 --> 00:04:24,340
 It's really JavaScript came from C

87
00:04:24,340 --> 00:04:26,940
 more than it came from Java.

88
00:04:26,940 --> 00:04:29,460
 There's a few things that are imitating Java.

89
00:04:29,460 --> 00:04:33,060
 And so all of the things above this line

90
00:04:33,060 --> 00:04:37,180
 are semicolon and curly brace.

91
00:04:37,180 --> 00:04:39,940
 They use semicolon and curly brace to end lines

92
00:04:39,940 --> 00:04:41,500
 and to begin and end blocks.

93
00:04:41,500 --> 00:04:43,780
 Curly brace, beginning curly brace, and end curly brace.

94
00:04:43,780 --> 00:04:46,620
 And then there is this other set of programming languages

95
00:04:46,620 --> 00:04:48,460
 that don't use semicolon and curly brace.

96
00:04:48,460 --> 00:04:50,500
 And C was the first language

97
00:04:50,500 --> 00:04:52,620
 that did the semicolon and curly brace.

98
00:04:52,620 --> 00:04:56,740
 And so these languages that are kind of below this line,

99
00:04:56,740 --> 00:05:01,140
 Bash, Perl, Python, and PHP are really,

100
00:05:01,140 --> 00:05:04,460
 actually PHP is a semicolon and curly brace as well.

101
00:05:04,460 --> 00:05:06,500
 Python is the language we've been learning,

102
00:05:06,500 --> 00:05:09,460
 and it's really the odd language.

103
00:05:09,460 --> 00:05:12,420
 So we're going to learn a language that's in the category

104
00:05:12,420 --> 00:05:14,020
 that makes it easier for you to learn C,

105
00:05:14,020 --> 00:05:15,820
 or C++, or Java, or Objective-C.

106
00:05:15,820 --> 00:05:20,140
 And so this is worth learning, even though you know Python.

107
00:05:20,140 --> 00:05:23,060
 There was another movement that was sort of,

108
00:05:23,060 --> 00:05:25,260
 C is a very high performance language

109
00:05:25,260 --> 00:05:27,860
 and really aimed computer scientists

110
00:05:27,860 --> 00:05:30,660
 to build complex systems like Linux.

111
00:05:30,660 --> 00:05:34,100
 But then there were languages for like the end user

112
00:05:34,100 --> 00:05:36,940
 that just got work done but weren't seen as like

113
00:05:36,940 --> 00:05:39,660
 super performant for professionals,

114
00:05:39,660 --> 00:05:41,340
 et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

115
00:05:41,340 --> 00:05:44,060
 And so Bash, which is the Linux shell

116
00:05:44,060 --> 00:05:46,940
 where you're typing CD and LS if you're familiar with that.

117
00:05:46,940 --> 00:05:48,900
 Perl was a report generation language

118
00:05:48,900 --> 00:05:52,100
 that introduced the concept of associative arrays.

119
00:05:52,100 --> 00:05:55,900
 And most people joke about Perl.

120
00:05:55,900 --> 00:05:58,460
 I don't like Perl 'cause I can never read my code

121
00:05:58,460 --> 00:05:59,300
 after I write it.

122
00:05:59,300 --> 00:06:01,620
 I can write it, but I can't read it afterwards.

123
00:06:01,620 --> 00:06:03,580
 But it introduced a lot of wonderful concepts

124
00:06:03,580 --> 00:06:05,580
 like associative arrays,

125
00:06:05,580 --> 00:06:07,820
 which we would call dictionaries in Python.

126
00:06:07,820 --> 00:06:12,380
 And Perl, it really definitely influenced Python

127
00:06:12,380 --> 00:06:14,220
 because of its ease of programming.

128
00:06:14,220 --> 00:06:17,580
 So what Perl was really good at was allowing a person

129
00:06:17,580 --> 00:06:21,700
 with very little formal training on data structures

130
00:06:21,700 --> 00:06:23,420
 to be able to use associative arrays

131
00:06:23,420 --> 00:06:25,140
 and nested associative arrays

132
00:06:25,140 --> 00:06:27,780
 to create pretty sophisticated data structures.

133
00:06:27,780 --> 00:06:30,540
 And Python came along with that.

134
00:06:30,540 --> 00:06:33,700
 And PHP also, original PHP stood

135
00:06:33,700 --> 00:06:36,380
 for Perl Hypertext Processor.

136
00:06:36,380 --> 00:06:37,660
 Now it doesn't stand for that.

137
00:06:37,660 --> 00:06:41,300
 But Perl and Python and PHP are in this category

138
00:06:41,300 --> 00:06:44,580
 of sort of interpreted, easy to use languages

139
00:06:44,580 --> 00:06:46,700
 with strings that work really nice.

140
00:06:46,700 --> 00:06:49,340
 And they just make life a lot easier.

141
00:06:49,340 --> 00:06:52,540
 In languages like C, strings are very difficult.

142
00:06:52,540 --> 00:06:56,220
 So if we take a look at this, right?

143
00:06:56,220 --> 00:06:57,580
 We've learned Python

144
00:06:57,580 --> 00:06:59,380
 and we're going to learn JavaScript next.

145
00:06:59,380 --> 00:07:00,980
 And so we're moving in.

146
00:07:00,980 --> 00:07:02,780
 But again, JavaScript you can think of

147
00:07:02,780 --> 00:07:05,340
 as unlocking a whole bunch of other languages.

148
00:07:05,340 --> 00:07:08,100
 And so it's worth learning it a little bit.

149
00:07:08,100 --> 00:07:09,500
 Even though in this class,

150
00:07:09,500 --> 00:07:12,060
 we're not going to go into any great detail

151
00:07:12,060 --> 00:07:14,380
 'cause mostly you're gonna be cutting and pasting JavaScript

152
00:07:14,380 --> 00:07:17,020
 and then tweaking it and reading it and debugging it.

153
00:07:17,020 --> 00:07:18,740
 So we're really not focusing

154
00:07:18,740 --> 00:07:21,220
 on writing too much new JavaScript.

155
00:07:21,220 --> 00:07:23,860
 So there's a couple of situations

156
00:07:23,860 --> 00:07:26,300
 where you'll find yourself writing some JavaScript.

157
00:07:26,300 --> 00:07:29,380
 One is augmenting HTML.

158
00:07:29,380 --> 00:07:30,980
 That'll be the first thing we'll do.

159
00:07:30,980 --> 00:07:34,460
 There is this thing in the browser that runs JavaScript.

160
00:07:34,460 --> 00:07:37,420
 And the way it interacts with the browser's UI

161
00:07:37,420 --> 00:07:39,900
 is through the document object model.

162
00:07:39,900 --> 00:07:42,340
 You can add a library like jQuery

163
00:07:42,340 --> 00:07:44,100
 to make that interaction easier

164
00:07:44,100 --> 00:07:45,460
 'cause the document object models

165
00:07:45,460 --> 00:07:47,140
 aren't as portable across browsers

166
00:07:47,140 --> 00:07:48,700
 as we would like sometimes.

167
00:07:48,700 --> 00:07:51,780
 And then to keep going,

168
00:07:51,780 --> 00:07:53,300
 you find that you're building more and more

169
00:07:53,300 --> 00:07:55,460
 of your application logic in the browser.

170
00:07:55,460 --> 00:07:56,700
 And so they say, you know what?

171
00:07:56,700 --> 00:07:59,540
 I just want to write the model in view part,

172
00:07:59,540 --> 00:08:02,300
 maybe, I mean, the controller in view part

173
00:08:02,300 --> 00:08:06,420
 in the browser in JavaScript using a templating language.

174
00:08:06,420 --> 00:08:09,780
 And you can use like Viewer React to do that.

175
00:08:09,780 --> 00:08:11,100
 And then if you keep on going,

176
00:08:11,100 --> 00:08:12,980
 you can add JavaScript as just a language.

177
00:08:12,980 --> 00:08:15,180
 And they've implemented it inside the server

178
00:08:15,180 --> 00:08:17,340
 using as a server-based language.

179
00:08:17,340 --> 00:08:19,060
 And we would use Django and Python

180
00:08:19,060 --> 00:08:20,220
 as our server-based language,

181
00:08:20,220 --> 00:08:22,940
 but you can actually write your entire application

182
00:08:22,940 --> 00:08:25,260
 front to back in JavaScript

183
00:08:25,260 --> 00:08:28,020
 and use something like Node to run the server side of it

184
00:08:28,020 --> 00:08:30,020
 that's actually talking to the database.

185
00:08:30,020 --> 00:08:32,620
 So there's lots and lots.

186
00:08:32,620 --> 00:08:35,180
 JavaScript is just like you're opening the door

187
00:08:35,180 --> 00:08:38,060
 into a lot of really wonderful capabilities.

188
00:08:38,060 --> 00:08:42,660
 So like I said, it is in the syntax family of Java,

189
00:08:42,660 --> 00:08:46,860
 and that is that it has semicolons to end lines,

190
00:08:46,860 --> 00:08:48,620
 whitespace doesn't matter,

191
00:08:48,620 --> 00:08:51,380
 open curly brace and close curly brace,

192
00:08:51,380 --> 00:08:52,780
 start and end blocks,

193
00:08:52,780 --> 00:08:56,780
 whereas in Python, you just end a line

194
00:08:56,780 --> 00:08:59,900
 and you indent to indicate a block of text

195
00:08:59,900 --> 00:09:02,740
 and you de-indent to indicate the end of that block of text.

196
00:09:02,740 --> 00:09:07,740
 Now, I will admit that Python is not my favorite syntax.

197
